UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT DEPARTMENT, THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, THREE SHRINK-WRAPPED CARDBOARD CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING SIXTY, TWELVE OUNCE PLASTIC BOTTLES, WERE PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE CAPS ON SIX BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY SIXTY OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED OTHER BOTTLES INSIDE THE THREE DAMAGED CARTONS.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING TYVEK SUITS, GLOVES, AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, AFFECTED SHRINK-WRAP, AND SIX DAMAGED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TWENTY GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE CONTENTS OF THE THREE DAMAGED CARTONS WERE CLEANED AND FORWARDED INSIDE THE ORIGINAL PACKAGING, ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT, TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

DRIVER DISCOVERED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER ONTO CONCRETE.  THE RIVERSIDE COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND APPLIED SAND TO FORM A CONTAINMENT BERM.  THE SAND WAS NOT CONTAMINATED BY THE FREE PRODUCT.  JONES MOTOR COMPANY, INC. DISPATCHED OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC.  APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE AFFECTED CONCRETE SURFACE.  OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES,  INC.  TRANSFERRED THE FREIGHT FROM THE LEAKING TRAILER INTO A REEFER TRUCK TO ASSIST WITH COOLING THE MATERIAL.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE FREIGHT, OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, IN.C DISCOVERED SEVEN PALLETS, EACH CONTAINING THIRTY-SIX CARDBOARD CARTONS OF TWO,  TWO AND ONE-HALF GALLON PLASTIC PAILS, OF DAMAGED MATERIAL APPROXIMATELY THIRTY GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS A RESULT OF IMPLOSION OF THE PAILS DUE TO HEAT.  OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. PLACED THE 252 DAMAGED CARTONS AND 504 DAMAGED PAILS INTO THIRTY-TWO, NINETY-FIVE GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUMS.  OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. TRANSPORTED THE THIRTY-TWO OVERPACK DRUMS TO THE REDOX CHEMICALS, INC. FACILITY IN BURLEY, IDAHO.  OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. GENERATED TEN, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS OF USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAMINATED CARTONS, ALONG WITH A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER CONTAINING ADDITIONAL CONTAMINATED CARTONS AND THE CONTAMINATED PALLETS. OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. TRANSPORTED THE TEN RECOVERY DRUMS TO CROSBY & OVERTON INC. OF LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA.  CROSBY & OVERTON INC. WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE DRUMS VIA INCINERATION, OCEAN BLUE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. TRANSPORTED THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER TO FILTER RECYCLING IN RIALTO, CALIFORNIA FOR RECYCLING. UTLX 200863, LOAD ISOPROPANOL, REPORTED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN SELKIRK, NY.  THE TRAINMASTER ON THE SCENE REPORTED THE CAR HAD A FAST DRIP FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP.  CSXT PERSONNEL TIGHTENED THE NOZZLE CAP AND SLOWED THE DRIP.  THE CAR WAS MOVED OVER THE SPILL CONTAINMENT PANS AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO MAKE REPAIRS.  THE SHIPPER, DOW CHEMICAL FOR UNION CARBIDE, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CONTRACTOR DRAINED THE BOV EXTENSION PIPE, REMOVED THE NOZZLE CAP AND FOUND THE GASKET WAS BADLY DETERIORATED.  THE CONTRACTOR INSTALL A NEW GASKET AND SECURED THE NOZZLE CAP WRENCH TIGHT.  THE LEAK STOPPED.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE DEFECT.

column168: A SWITCH CREW AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN BALDWIN, FL, REPORTED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR AROUND A CITX 33465, LOAD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. THE SHIPPER, YARA NORTH AMERICA, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND CSXT RESPONDED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REPORTED A VAPOR LEAK AROUND THE PRESSURE PLATE WHERE THE PRESSURE PLATE IS BOLTED TO THE TANK NOZZLE FLANGE.  ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO TIGHTEN THE FLANGE BOLTS WITH HAND TOOLS BUT TO NO AVAIL.  THE CONTRACTOR OBTAINED AN AIR DRIVEN IMPACT WRENCH AND TIGHTEN THE FLANGE BOLTS.  THE VAPOR LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

THE DECONTAMINATED THE CAR WHERE THE PRODUCT HAD FLOWED DOWN THE SIDES AND CLEAN UP THE IMPACTED BALLAST UNDER THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: OPERATOR WAS UNLOADING RAIL CAR INTO TRAILER WHEN HE HEARD A HISSING SOUND FROM THE RAIL CAR RELIEF VALVE.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE COMPRESSOR AND OPENED A VAPOR PURGE VALVE TO VENT THE RAIL CAR PRESSURE INTO THE PROCESS.  THE RELIEF VALVE RESEATED, AND THE RELEASE CEASED.  OPERATOR NOTIFIED CORPORATE OFFICE.  REMAINDER OF MATERIAL IN RAIL CAR WAS GRAVITY FED INTO PROCESS.  THEY WERE NO OFF-SITE COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR, NO EVACUATIONS WERE MADE, AND NO INJURIES REPORTED.  LESS THAN 25 POUNDS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED.  INTERNAL INVESTIGATION IN PROGRESS. INITIAL INDICATION IS THAT THE NORMAL PRESSURE BUILD UP DURING UNLOADING CAUSED THE SAFETY VALVE TO LIFT, POSSIBLY PREMATURELY AS IT MAY HAVE BEEN WEAKENED FROM A RELEASE 2 DAYS PRIOR.

OPERATOR WAS UNLOADING RAIL CAR INTO TRAILER WHEN HE NOTICED THE FLOW SLOW DOWN AND HEARD A HISSING NOISE.  HE SAW VAPOR IN THE AREA OF THE DOME OF THE RAIL CAR.  OPERATOR OPENED VALVE TO VENT THE PRESSURE IN THE RAIL CAR TO THE PROCESS.  OPERATOR CALLED 9-1-1 AND THE CORPORATE OFFICE.   FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND CLOSED THE LIQUID VALVE ON THE RAIL CAR. WE REQUESTED THEY CHECK VALVES AND FITTINGS UNDER RAIL CAR DOME WITH LITMUS PAPER FOR ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  NO ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE WAS NOTED. THERE WERE NO OFF-SITE COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR, NO EVACUATIONS WERE MADE, AND NO INJURIES REPORTED.  LESS THAN 25 POUNDS WAS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED.  INTERNAL INVESTIGATION IN PROGRESS.  INITIAL INDICATION IS THAT FLOW WAS DEAD-HEADED FROM VALVE BEING CLOSED, CAUSING OVERPRESSURE AND AN AMMONIA RELEASE FROM EITHER THE SAFETY VALVE OR THE LIQUID CONNECTION ON THE RAIL CAR.

column168: AT CSC TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN HAMLET, NC, YARD JOB, Y39004 WAS MAKING A REVERSE MOVE AND DERAILED 4 CARS AND SIDESWIPED ENGINE, CSXT2419 CAUSING A GASH IN THE SIDE OF TANK CAR, ONTX1027, LOAD ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES, LIQUID, NOS (ETHYLENE GLYCOL).  AN ESTIMATED 16,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED ON THE CROSSOVER ON THE LEAD TRACK IN THE YARD.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO CONDUCT THE CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE SHIPPER, SABIC MARKETING, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  STATE AND FEDERAL ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCIES WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  THE CONTRACTOR PUMPED APPROXIMATELY 4,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE DAMAGED TANK CAR. COLLECTION TRENCHES WERE EXCAVATED IN THE AREA AND ABOUT 1,500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED FROM THE GROUND.  ALL RECOVERED PRODUCT WAS PROCESSED AND TRANSPORTED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP IS CONTINUING.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS: DATE 5/6/02 - 0115 P.F.I., INC/NORTHWEST PETROLEUM DRIVER PICKED UP LOAD OF GASOLINE AT MOTIVA NEWARK TERMINAL FOR DELIVERY TO ANDOVER TEXACO SERVICE STATION LOCATED AT 33 MAIN STREET, ANDOVER BORO, NEW JERSEY.  UPON ARRIVAL AT STATION DRIVER HOOKED UP HOSE TO TRAILER COMPARTMENT AND UNDER GROUND TANK FILL CONNECTION.  OPENED DISCHARGE VALVE AND STARTED UNLOADING GASOLINE.  WHILE WAITING FOR COMPARTMENT TO EMPTY DRIVER NOTICED GASOLINE FLOWING OUT OF THE SPILL CONTAINMENT BUCKET.  HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED DISCHARGE VALVE.  GASOLINE CONTINUED TO FLOW UNTIL HOSE WAS EMPTY.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION DRIVER FOUND THAT HOSE AT FITTING HAD RUPTURED.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TRIED TO CONTAIN THE FLOW OF GASOLINE AND CALLED PERS (PROFESSIONAL EMERGENCY RESOURCE SERVICES) WHOM P.F.I., INC., SUBSCRIBES TO THEIR SERVICES.  PERS IMMEDIATELY CALLED HMHTTC RESPONSE TEAM AT PARSIPPANY, NJ.  RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED IN APPROXIMATELY ON HOUR, 0345. THEY LAID DOWN SIX BAGS OF SPEEDY DRY.  THEY SHOVELED AND SWEPT UP SPEEDY DRY AND PUT INTO A SINGLE 55 GALLON DRUM WHICH THEY SEALED.  THEY LEFT SPILL SITE AFTER CLEANUP AT APPROXIMATELY 0500.  WE INSPECTED ALL THE OTHER HOSES WE CARRY ON OUR TRAILER.  ALL APPEAR TO BE IN VERY GOOD CONDITION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE,  FIFTY POUND PAPER ON A SKID WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT INSIDE THE TRAILER. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 10, THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. VEHICLE WAS CLIPPED BY ANOTHER VEHICLE, WHICH CAUSED THE TRUCK TO GO OFF THE ROAD AND OVERTURN.  LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO INSPECT THE SITE.  INTERSTATE 10 WAS SHUT DOWN FOR FURTHER DETERMINATION OF PRODUCT RELEASED.  BAYER CORPORATION RESPONDED TO PERFORM PRODUCT TRANSFER. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OF PENSACOLA, FLORIDA WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE SITE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF FREE LIQUID WERE RELEASED FROM THE CLEANOUT PORT ON THE TANK.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO ABSORB THE FREE LIQUID, AND EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM THE IMPACTED AREA.  FIVE (5) 55-GALLON DRUMS OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SOIL WERE GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP.  DISPOSAL WILL BE COORDINATED DIRECTLY BY SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES, PER LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY, THE HOSE ON THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. CARGO TANK RUPTURED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE HUNDRED GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA, THE CARGO TANK, AND THE WALLS AND TANKS OF THE FACILITY.  OP-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF ROCHESTER, NEW YORK RESPONDED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. OP-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. USED A VACUUM AND APPLIED ABSORBENT PADS AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL, ALONG WITH ACETONE AND XYLENE, TO REMOVE THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE AFFECTED SURFACES.  OP-TECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. GENERATED THREE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUMS OF USED ABSORBENT PADS AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL, WHICH WERE DISPOSED OF AT THE CYCLE CHEM LANDFILL FACILITY IN LEWISBERRY, PENNSYLVANIA.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

WHILE LOADING AN IMPORT SHIPMENT INTO A KINTETSU WORLDWIDE TRUCK, OUR FORKLIFT OPERATOR, AN EMPLOYEE OF ALLIANCE AIRLINES, STRUCK A 15 LITRE STEEL JERRICAN (3A1) OF UN1866, RESIN SOLUTION, PG II WITH THE PIECE OF CARGO THAT HE WAS LOADING,  THIS JERRICAN OF RESIN SOLUTION, WHICH THE DRIVER HAD PICKED UP EARLIER FROM JAL CARGO, HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE FLOOR AT THE TAIL END OF THE TRAILER.  THE JERRICAN WAS CRUSHED BETWEEN THE SKID OF CARGO THAT OUR DOCKHAND WAS LOADING & THE SIDEWALL OF THE TRAILER.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS UNAWARE THAT HE HAD STRUCK THE DGR PIECE INSIDE THE TRUCK AND CONTINUED DRIVING ANOTHER 6.1 METERS BEFORE STOPPING.  WHEN HE FINALLY REALIZED THAT HE HAD DAMAGED THE DGR PIECE IN THE TRAILER, HE BACKED OUT WITH THE SKID THAT HAD CAUSED THE DAMAGE.  THE DAMAGED JERRICAN REMAINED 6.1 METERS INSIDE THE TRAILER WHERE APPROXIMATELY 7 OR 8 LITRES HAD LEAKED OUT.  THE DAMAGED DGR WAS SECURED N A RECOVERY DRUM, AND HAZCHEM WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSAL.  ALL LEAKAGE WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL-SPILL MATERIALS, AS DIRECTED BY CHEMTREC, WRAPPED IN PLASTIC, AND SECURED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.

ON MAY 26, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 1201 HOURS, A LOUISIANA STATE TROOPER DISCOVERED A LEAKING RAILWAY TANK CAR DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) LATANIER, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD.  THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS GATX 32125, CONTAINING ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS LIQUID, N.O.S., 9, UN3082, PG III.  THE STATE TROOPER TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP 3/4 TURN, THUS REDUCING THE LEAK FROM 1 DRIP PER 2 SECONDS TO 1 DRIP PER 20 SECONDS.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONDER WHO, UPON ARRIVAL, OPENED AND CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CREATING A TIGHT SEAL TO VERIFY THAT THE VALVE WAS NOT LEAKING.  THE RESPONDER THEN TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WRENCH TIGHT.  THE RECOVERED, SPILLED LADING WAS TAKEN TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.

ON MAY 13, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 1750 HOURS, RAILWAY TANK CAR GATX 62584, CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID, 8, UN1789, PG II WAS REPORTED LEAKING WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI RAILROAD YARD.  THE CREW ON DUTY REPORTED A LEAK FOLLOWED BY AN ODOR.  KCS DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONDER WHO, UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE CARS, REPORTED THAT THE RELEASE ORIGINATED FROM A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  THE RESPONDER DECONTAMINATED THE CAR AND REPLACED THE RUPTURE DISK, THUS CORRECTING THE RELEASE.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: THIS CARGO ARRIVED LOADED ON A MD-11 MAIN DECK UNIT FROM FRANKFURT, GERMANY.  THESE BOXES WERE STACKED AS A WALL OF BOXES AGAINST A LARGE CRATE.  UPON REMOVING THE CARGO NET, APPROXIMATELY 15 BOXES (THE TOP 2 ROWS) FELL TO THE GROUND FROM A HEIGHT OF ABOUT TEN FEET.  OF THE 15 BOXES THAT FELL, 6-4 LITRE BOXES WERE EITHER LEAKING, OR SHOWED EVIDENCE OF BEING LEAKED UPON.  THE WAREHOUSE STAFF IMMEDIATELY DONNED THEIR GLOVES, AND SPREAD ABSORBENT MATERIALS ON THE GROUND.  THE 6 LEAKING BOXES WERE "REPACKED" ONTO A LARGE PLASTIC SHEET ATOP A WOODEN PALLET AND BEDDED INTO APPROXIMATELY 30 LBS. OF ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THE PACKAGE WAS WRAPPED WITH THE PLASTIC SHEETING, TAPED AND SHRINK-WRAPPED, AND SET ASIDE. THERE WERE NO APPARENT INJURIES TO THE STAFF.  ALL GOVERNMENT AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED, WITH THE F.A.A. EXPECTED TO DO A FOLLOW-UP REPORT UNDER SEPARATE COVER.  THIS INCIDENT HAS BEEN FORWARDED TO THE MANAGEMENT, AND CHANGES TO THE LOADING PRACTICES ARE EXPECTED.
SHIPMENT WAS IMPROPERLY PACKAGED.  PAILS WERE TAPED CLOSED WITH DUCT TAPE.

column168: WHILE ATTEMPTING A LEFT TURN INTO A STATION THE DRIVER HEARD A LOUD POPPING NOISE AND CONSEQUENTLY THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE INTO THE DITCH WITH THE TRUCK STILL ATTACHED.  A PORTION OF THE TRACTOR 5TH WHEEL SEPARATED FROM THE TRACTOR CAUSING THE TRAILER TO ROLLOVER.  THE TRAILER WAS PUNCTURED IN THE ROLLOVER.  ROBERTS GARAGE CAME TO UPRIGHT THE TRAILER. THE PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER WAS PUMPED TO ANOTHER TRAILER THAT HAD BEEN WEIGHED EMPTY THAT WEIGHED WITH THE PRODUCT.  THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WAS CALLED AND INCIDENT REPORT #04 0524-1530-KAH WAS ISSUED.  INDUSTRIAL & PETROLEUM ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC. HANDLED THE CLEANUP.  WE DO NOT HAVE INVOICES/COSTS FOR CLEANUP TO ATTACH TO THIS REPORT.

SOUTH CAROLINA HIGHWAY PATROL BELIEVED THEY OBSERVED VAPOR BEING RELEASED FROM AN IBC (TOTE CONTAINER) ON FLATBED TRAILER.  AFTER FOLLOWING FOR EIGHT (8) MILES PULLED VEHICLE TO SIDE OF INTERSTATE 95 (MM 56 NORTH).  AFTER CHECKING BILL OF LADING, OFFICER FELT THE INCIDENT TO BE A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RELEASE AND CLOSED ALL NORTHBOUND LANES OF INTERSTATE AND CONTACTED LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  ON ARRIVAL, FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZMAT TEAM SET UP PERIMETER, DONNED LEVEL A PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND ENTERED SCENE.  ENTRY TEAM MONITORED FOR HAZARDOUS VAPORS (HYDROCHLORIC ACID & CHLORINE), FOUND NONE.  ENTRY TEAM USED ABSORBENT PAD AND WIPED AREA AROUND IBC COVER.  ENTRY TEAM THEN RETURNED THROUGH DECONTAMINATION AREA AND SCENE WAS DECLARED SAFE.  ONE LANE OF INTERSTATE WAS OPENED AT 12:00 (NOON) AND ALL LANES WERE REOPENED BY 12:20 PM.

THE DRIVER WAS IN THE LOADING PROCESS WHEN THE CUSTOMERS SAFETY CHAIN BROKE.  THIS ALLOWED THE LOADING SPOUT TO LIFT UP OUT OF THE DOME LID AREA. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE LOADING PROCESS DOWN.  APPROX. 20 GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED, PLANT PERSONNEL RESPONDED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  PLANT MAINTENANCE INSTALLED A NEW SAFETY CHAIN AND LOADING RESUMED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE (1) 300-GALLON TOTE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  APPARENTLY, THE TOTE HAD A FAULTY VALVE, WHICH RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PPE, AMPHOMAG, DUST PAN, AND BROOM.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE (1) 5-GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM TO BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSAL.  THE LEAKING TOTE WAS SECURED AND HELD IN A CONTAINMENT POOL PENDING SHIPPER DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: A CENTER EMPLOYEE REPORTED A WET PACKAGE WITH A FLAMMABLE LIQUID DIAMOND LABEL AT 19:30.  TRINA NGUYEN RESPONDED TO THE LEAKER AT THAT TIME.  TRINA WORE BOOTS, AN APRON, GOGGLES AND GREEN GLOVES.  TRINA FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  NO LIQUID LEAKED OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE.  ONLY THE CARDBOARD BOX WAS WET.  THE PACKAGE CONTAINED FOUR ONE GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES OF ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL.  THE CAP ON ONE OF THE FOUR BOXES WAS LOOSE, ALLOWING THE LIQUID TO LEAK.  THE LEAKING LIQUID REMAINING IN THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS SOLIDIFIED AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.  THE THREE REMAINING BOTTLES HAD NO RESIDUE FROM THE LEAK AND WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  FUTURE LEAKERS MAY BE PREVENTED IF ALL CAPS ARE SUFFICIENTLY TIGHTENED ONTO THE BOTTLES.

column168: MAY 31, 2004, SES WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 7:50 AM OF A POTENTIAL RELEASE OF CRUDE OIL TO THE ENVIRONMENT AS A RESULT OF AN OVERTURNED TANKER TRUCK,  TRACTOR #815 AND TRAILER #934.  THE ACCIDENT WAS A RESULT OF A PORTION OF LOW GAP ROAD, OUTSIDE OF ONEIDA, TN, GIVING WAY AS THE VEHICLE WAS PASSING OVER IT, RESULTING IN THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER LAYING DOWN ON ITS' SIDE.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSPORTING CRUDE OIL FROM OIL WELLS, LOCATED IN AND AROUND TN TO THE SOMERSET REFINERY FACILITY, LOCATED IN SOMERSET, KY.  AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, THE TRAILER WAS TRANSPORTING APPROXIMATELY 191 BARRELS, 8,000 GALLONS, OF CRUDE OIL.  UPON NOTIFICATION OF THE ACCIDENT, SES MOBILIZED PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT TO THE SITE.  IN ADDITION, SES CONTACTED BILL GOODWIN, A MANAGER FOR THE TENNESSEE OIL & GAS ASSOCIATION (TOGA), REQUESTING ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE FOR CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP ACTIVITIES.  AT APPROXIMATELY 9:20 AM, SES CONTACTED THE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY'S NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC).  SES FILED AN INITIAL REPORT SUMMARIZING THE INCIDENT AND WAS PROVIDED INCIDENT REPORT# 723512.  AT APPROXIMATELY 10:15 AM, MEMBERS OF TOGA ARRIVED ON THE SITE.  THE WEATHER CONDITIONS UPON ARRIVING ON SITE WERE A TEMPERATURE OF 60 DEGREES FAHRENHEIT AND A MISTY RAIN WAS FALLING. WATER LEVELS IN THE NEW RIVER WERE REPORTED TO BE HIGH BECAUSE OF RECENT RAIN EVENTS IN THE AREA.  IT WAS ASSESSED THAT THE FOURTH (4TH) COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER HAD BEGUN TO LEAK CRUDE OIL TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE INTEGRITY OF THE FOURTH (4TH) COMPARTMENT HAD NOT BEEN BREACHED BUT THE SEALS ON THE MAN WAY HAD BEGUN TO FAIL.  THE RELEASED CRUDE OIL WAS COLLECTING AND MIXING WITH RUNOFF WATER IN AN ADJACENT DITCH LINE.  THE DITCH LINE EMPTIED INTO THE NEW RIVER.  TOGA'S INITIAL CLEANUP ACTIVITIES INCLUDED PLACING PETROLEUM ABSORBENT BOOMS ACROSS THE NEW RIVER AND THE DITCH LINE AND PLACING PETROLEUM ABSORBENT PADS IN THE DITCH LINE. SES PERSONNEL ARRIVED WHILE TOGA WAS PLACING ABSORBENTS AND BEGAN ASSISTING IN THE PLACEMENT.  THE INITIAL ABSORBENT BOOM ACROSS THE NEW RIVER WAS SECURED AT APPROXIMATELY 10:45 AM.  CRUDE OIL SHEEN WAS OBSERVED ON THE NEW RIVER AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 AM.  SES'S VACUUM TRUCK ARRIVED ON SITE AND BEGAN VACUUMING CRUDE OIL AND IMPACTED WATER FROM THE DITCH LINE.  A SECOND TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS BROUGHT TO THE SITE TO OFFLOAD THE CRUDE OIL FROM THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY TWENTY (20) BARRELS, 840 GALLONS, OF CRUDE OIL WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT. ATTACHED IN APPENDIX B IS A COPY OF THE SOMERSET REFINERY RECEIVING TICKET AND COPIES OF THE SOUTH KENTUCKY PURCHASING COMPANY, INC. CRUDE OIL PICK-UP & DELIVERY TICKETS.  UPON COMPLETION OF OFF LOADING OF THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE, A WRECKER SERVICE WAS CONTACTED AND BROUGHT IN TO REMOVER THE OVERTURNED TRACTOR AND TRAILER.  ATTACHED IN APPENDIX C ARE PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN DURING THE DAY, DOCUMENTING THE EVENTS.  GLENN BURKE, AN INSPEC

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE LOCATION, DRIVER NOTICED TRAILER WAS LEAKING.  DRIVER SUITED UP AND CHECKED OUT THE TRAILER.  HE FOUND OUT ONE SIDE OF THE DOME WAS TIGHTEN TOO MUCH ON THE LEFT SIDE THAT CAUSED THE DOME GASKET TO FALL INSIDE THE DOME.  PRODUCT HAD SPLIT OUT OF THE DOME LID AREA BECAUSE OF THE OPENING BETWEEN DOME COLLAR AND DOME LID, WHICH IS NORMALLY WERE THE GASKET SETS.  IN ADDITION, ONE LATCH THAT IS USED TO CLOSE THE DOME WAS CROSS-THREADED, WHICH MADE IT DIFFICULT TO OPEN.  THE GUARD AND DISPATCH WERE NOTIFIED.  CUSTOMER CONTACTED PERSONNEL TO CLEAN SPILL.  A HALF PINT OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  DOME LID WAS OPENED AND GASKET REPLACED BY DRIVER. TYPICALLY TRAILER LOADED AND DOME LID SECURED BY SHIPPER.  IT IS SHIPPER POLICY NOT ALLOW DRIVER ON TOP OF UNIT AFTER LOADING.  DRIVER STATES ONE SIDE OF DOME LID WAS FOUND TO BE EXCESSIVELY TIGHTENED, WHICH, IN TURN CAUSED PORTION OF DOME GASKET TO FALL INSIDE THE DOME COLLAR.  NO GASKET MATERIAL FELL INSIDE TANK/PRODUCT.  POSITIONING OF DOME GASKET WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN VISIBLE UPON INSPECTION.  DOME GASKET WAS PUSHED TOWARD INTERNAL PORTION OF COLLAR.  DIRECT CAUSE - FAILURE OF DOME LID SEAL.  INDIRECT CAUSE - IMPROPER SECURING OF DOME LID BY SHIPPER.  ACTION - INCIDENT REVIEWED WITH SHIPPER.  MONITOR FOR TRENDS.

column168: ON MAY 26, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 1201 HOURS, A LOUISIANA STATE TROOPER DISCOVERED A LEAKING RAILWAY TANK CAR DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) LATANIER, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD.  THE LEAKING TANK CAR WAS GATX 32125, CONTAINING ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS LIQUID, N.O.S., 9, UN3082, PG III.  THE STATE TROOPER TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP 3/4 TURN, THUS REDUCING THE LEAK FROM 1 DRIP PER 2 SECONDS TO 1 DRIP PER 20 SECONDS.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONDER WHO, UPON ARRIVAL, OPENED AND CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CREATING A TIGHT SEAL TO VERIFY THAT THE VALVE WAS NOT LEAKING.  THE RESPONDER THEN TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WRENCH TIGHT.  THE RECOVERED, SPILLED LADING WAS TAKEN TO THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, 5-2-04, BLAINE STETTLER.  ON CALL PATIENT SERVICE TECHNICIAN, APRIA HEALTHCARE, WILLIAMSPORT, PA. RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM THE APRIA ANSWERING SERVICE THAT AN UNKNOWN INDIVIDUAL HAD REPORTED THAT THERE WAS A CLOUD AROUND THE BASE OF THE OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID STAND TANK AT THE BRANCH.  STETTLER RESPONDED TO THE FACILITY AND UPON ARRIVAL OBSERVED A WHITE FOG AROUND THE BASE OF THE STAND TANK AND HEARD A HISSING NOISE.  UPON INSPECTION HE FOUND THAT A VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY TIGHTENED AND THAT THE HISSING NOISE AND CLOUD WAS COMING FROM THE PRIMARY FILL VALVE.  THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF LIQUID BEING RELEASED FROM THE TANK.  THE VALVE WAS SECURED AND THE AREA PROTECTED UNTIL THE CLOUD DISSIPATED.  WHILE WAITING FOR THE CLOUD TO DISSIPATE HE CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR, ROBERT SAAR, TRANSPORTATION LEAD, WHO NOTIFIED APRIA HEALTHCARE, CORPORATE TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  ONCE THE CLOUD HAD DISSIPATED AN INSPECTION WAS MADE OF THE STAND TANK AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ICE HAD FORMED ON THE CONCRETE BELOW THE VALVE.  A REVIEW OF THE STAND TANK LOG WAS MADE.  IT WAS ASCERTAINED THAT 15" (APPROX. 315 GALLONS) OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (LOX) HAD BEEN RELEASED SINCE THE TANK WAS LAST USED.  THE LAST INDIVIDUAL TO USE THE TANK HAD BEEN DAVID MONG, PATIENT SERVICE TECHNICIAN, ON 5-1-04, WHEN HE FILLED HIS TRUCK MOUNTED VESSEL.  APPROPRIATE CORRECTIVE ACTION AND RETRAINING HAS BEEN COMPLETED WITH MONG.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, OR ANY COLLATERAL DAMAGE RELATED TO THIS INCIDENT.  THERE WAS NO CLEANUP OR EMERGENCY RESPONSE REQUIRED.

IV UNLOADING AT CONSIGNEE.  UNLOADER TOLD HIM THAT WHEN HE WAS ALMOST FINISHED UNLOADING TO CLOSE HIS VALVE PART WAY SO HE WOULD NOT BLOW AIR INTO THE TANK WHEN HE WENT EMPTY.  WHEN ID WAS ALMOST EMPTY HE CLOSED VALVE ON CONSIGNEE'S TANK THEN CLOSED VALVE ON TRAILER.  HE THEN CRACKED THE CUSTOMER VALVE AND THEN THE TRAILER VALVE TO CLEAR THE HOSE.  WHEN HE DID A FINE SPRAY OF THE PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE TOP OF THE 1/4" DIA 30' HIGH SIGHT TUBE.  ID HAD NOT BEEN TOLD THE SIGHT TUBE WAS VENTED.  MOST SIGHT TUBES ARE CLOSED.  THE FINE SPRAY LANDED ON AN EMPLOYEE, BERNIE WHO HAPPENED TO BE WALKING BY.  BERNIE WAS NOT WEARING PROTECTIVE GEAR. EMPLOYEE WENT TO WASH STATION AND WASHED.  HE CAME BACK AND SEEMED TO BE OK, OTHER THAN UPSET THAT THIS HAPPENS ALL THE TIME.  ID SPOKE W/MANAGER STEVE LEAR, WHO AGREED THE HAPPENS ALL THE TIME AND THAT THEY NEED TO DO SOMETHING ABOUT IT.  THEY WERE SORRY THEY HAD NOT TOLD ID THE SIGHT TUBE WAS VENTED.  THE SPRAY WAS SO FINE THAT WHEN IT HIT THE GROUND THERE WAS NOTHING TO CLEAN UP.  AMOUNT WAS ABOUT EQUAL TO 3 TO 4 SQUIRTS FROM A WATER BOTTLE.

column168: NON-PACKAGE FAILURE WHILE OFF LOADING JET-A(DURING A FIRE EMERGENCY) DRIVER (OPERATOR) PULLED RESIDUAL PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD CAUSING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE THROUGH VAPOR RECOVERY PLUMBING ONTO GROUND SURFACE.  CORRECTIVE  ACTION: DRIVER WILL HAVE SECOND PERSON WHEN OFF LOADING TO SECOND CARGO TANK.  DRIVERS WILL NEVER OFF LOAD ON UNPAVED SURFACE.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND PLACED IN (5) 55 GALLON DOT DRUMS.  ASBURY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE WILL DISPOSE OFF WASTE DIRT (WASTE EMERGENCY ID CALIF.CAC 0002577195) DRIVER JOHN MCARTHUR WAS TRANSFERRING JET-A FROM COOL'S TRAILER 14A THROUGH TRUCK 14'S PRODUCT PUMP DIRECTLY INTO A SEMI CARGO TANK OPERATED BY HEAVY LIFT AVIATION.  THIS TRANSFER WAS PERFORMED AT THE WEST END OF THE AIRPORT'S TARMAC SOUTH OF A HELIPAD ALONG A GRAVEL SERVICE ROAD.  JOHN MCARTHUR WAS POSITIONED ON THE GROUND MANNING HIS VEHICLE'S TRANSFER PUMP WHILE THE HEAVY LIFT OPERATOR WAS ON TOP OF HEAVY'S LIFT CARGO TANK OBSERVING THE PRODUCT TRANSFER THROUGH AN OPEN DOME LID.  DURING THE TRANSFER PROCESS PRODUCT BEGAN TO ESCAPE THROUGH 14A'S VAPOR PLUMBING.  JOHN IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  OBVIOUSLY 14A'S PRODUCT PUMP'S FOUR-WAY VALVE WAS PLACED IN THE WRONG POSITION.  THAT IS, INSTEAD OF OFFLOADING THE PRODUCT FROM 14A TO THE HEAVY LIFT TRAILER THE RESIDUAL PRODUCT IN THE HEAVY LIFT TRAILER WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE COOL TRAILER OVERFILLING 14A'S COMPARTMENT ESCAPING THROUGH 14A'S VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM TO THE GROUND.  JOHN CALLED COOL TRANSPORTS INFORMING DISPATCH OF THE SITUATION.  DISPATCH IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED COOL'S SAFETY MANAGER ROBERT HOFFMAN.  ROBERT AND AN ASSISTANT IMMEDIATELY TRAVELED TO FRENCH VALLEY AIRPORT.  WHILE IN ROUTE TO THE INCIDENT ROBERT CONTACTED ASBURY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO ENSURE THEY WOULD HAVE AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AVAILABLE IF NEEDED.  ROBERT THEN CONTACTED CALIFORNIA EPA FOR AN EMERGENCY SITE NUMBER (CAC 00022577195).  UPON ARRIVAL ROBERT ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND OUTLINED THE GROUND ABOUT THE CONTAMINATED AREA.  ROBERT AND AN ASSISTANT PLACED PLASTIC MATTING ON THE GROUND TO COLLECT THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  DURING ITS REMOVAL THE SOIL WAS FOUND TO BE HARD AND FIRMLY PACKED THEREFORE; THE PRODUCT DID NOT PERMEATE DEEP BELOW GROUND LEVEL.  AFTER REMOVING A GROUND AREA MEASURING 12'X12'X8" NO VISUAL TRACES OR AROMA OF FUEL WERE EVIDENT.  THE COLLECTED SOIL WAS THEN PLACED INTO SIX DOT 55 GALLON DRUMS, SEALED AND LABELED FOR TRANSPORT.  ASBURY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CONTACTED TO REMOVE THE SIX DRUMS, GIVEN COOL'S CALIFORNIA EPA EMERGENCY SITE NUMBER AND A SIGNED LETTER STATING THEY WILL ACT AS COOL'S AGENT FOR PICK-UP AND DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE DRUMS.  THE REMOVED SOIL AND GRAVEL WILL BE REPLACED.  THE SURFACE WILL BE GRADED TO ITS PRIOR CONDITION.  AFTER COOL TRANSPORTS RECEIVES THEIR COPY OF THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST FROM ASBURY ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES A COPY OF THE MANIFEST WILL BE FORWARDED WITH PHOTOS OF THE COMPLETED PROJECT TO AIR BP REPRESENTATIVES

AS PRO 537499266 WAS BEING UNLOADED THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR NOTICED LIQUID ON TOP OF THE 55 GAL DRUM.  OPERATOR TOLD SUPERVISOR WHO THEN CALLED JEFF TURNER.  CON-WAY HELD SHIPMENT UNTIL SHIPPER COULD BE CONTACTED AND GIVE INSTRUCTIONS OF CLEAN UP AND DISPOSITION.

ON 05/06/04 AT 0059 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR OF "JET FUEL" WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 208 (LINE 3, 6N AREA) OF OUR HAZMAT SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS JAMES SHEPPARD AND LOREN LORENZO DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THIS BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN A PLASTIC BAG THAT CONTAINED 1 X METAL PART WITH FUEL IN THE FUEL CELL.  THIS PART WAS DECLARED AS "DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS, 9, UN3363", THE CELLS ON THIS PART HAD PLASTIC FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES THAT WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  ONE OF THE CLOSURES CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THE PART TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 30 ML OF ITS CONTENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND HAD THE PROPER SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0133.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

I WAS CONTACTED BY TONY CARROLL ON FRIDAY, MAY 7, 2004 AT 1745 HOURS AND ADVISED OF A HAZMAT SPILL ON I-40 AT THE 193 MILE MARKER WESTBOUND.  I CONTACTED MECHANIC ASSISTANT JOSH HOLMES AND ADVISED HIM TO RESPOND ALSO. WE ARRIVED AT THE SHOP AT ABOUT 1800 HOURS AND IMMEDIATELY DEPARTED FOR THE SCENE.  WE ARRIVED ON SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 1910 HOURS.  DRIVER KENNY BURNETTE WAS ON THE SCENE WITH TRACTOR #337 AND TRAILER #32B.  I NOTED A TRAIL OF LIQUID RUNNING FROM THE TRAVELED ROAD SURFACE ONTO THE RIGHT SHOULDER AND LEADING UP TO THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  ARKANSAS STATE POLICE, PRAIRIE COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT AND HAZEN FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL WERE ALSO ON SCENE.  THEY ESTABLISHED TRAFFIC CONTROL AND SECURED THE SCENE.  THE OUTSIDE LANE OF I-40 WESTBOUND WAS BLOCKED OFF.  TRAFFIC CONTINUED TO FLOW IN THE INSIDE LANE.  TONY CARROLL, JOSH HOLMES AND I USED ONE OF OUR SPILL KITS TO CONTAIN THE POOL AS WELL AS WE COULD.  WE USED THE ABSORBENT PADS AND "SNAKES" FOR THAT PURPOSE.  I DIAGRAMED THE SCENE AND NOTED THAT THE NOTICEABLE TRAIL STARTED AT THE RIGHT EDGE OF THE TRAVELED ROAD SURFACE AND CONTINUED FOR 1022' AND ENDED AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS CENTERED ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER.  A TRAIL OF LIQUID WAS OBSERVED COMING FROM THE REAR DOOR AREA OF THE TRUCK AND WAS ALSO LEAKING FROM THE RIGHT SIDE WALL OF THE TRUCK.  THERE WAS A POOL OF LIQUID UNDER THE REAR DUALS OF THE TRAILER.  THE ENTIRE AREA FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER FORWARD FOR APPROXIMATELY 21' WAS LIQUID SOAKED AND RAN OFF TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER.  THE RIGHT SHOULD WAS SLOPED AT ABOUT A 25 DEGREE ANGLE AND THE FLUID TRAIL APPEARED TO FLOW STRAIGHT DOWNWARD IN A 21' WIDE PATH (SEE DIAGRAM).  THE FLUID FLOW CONTINUED TO THE TREE LINE AND INTO THE TREES WHERE IT FINALLY STOPPED AND POOLED IN A DRY CREEK BED.  THE FINAL POOL WA ABOUT 14' LONG BY 3' WIDE.  THE TOTAL AREA AFFECTED IS APPROXIMATELY 880 SQUARE FEET.  I OBSERVED THE TRAILER INTERIOR AND NOTED THE FOLLOWING: THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS A STANDARD SIZE CONTAINER, (APP. 4'X4'X4') SITTING ON A STANDARD SHIPPING PALLET.  THE AFFECTED CONTAINER WAS SITTING ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND WAS THE LAST UNIT AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD.  THERE WAS ALSO AN IDENTICAL CONTAINER ON THE RIGHT SIDE AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD. NEITHER CONTAINER PALLET APPEARED TO HAVE MOVE.  A STANDARD DRUM DOLLY WAS LOCATED AT THE RIGHT REAR OF THE TRAILER NEXT TO THE DOOR AND WAS PLACED ON THE FLOOR WITH THE WHEEL SIDE UP.  THE LEAKING CONTAINER ITSELF APPEARED TO BE NYLON OR TEFLON AND WAS COVERED BY METALLIC SHELL.  THERE IS A RECESSED OPENING AT THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE TANK FOR A DRAIN VALVE.  TO THE RIGHT OF THE VALVE (AS YOU LOOK DIRECTLY AT THE TANK), I SAW A LARGE CRACK IN THE CONTAINER WALL.  THE CRACK APPEARED TO BE 4 TO 6 INCHES LONG AS WAS ACTIVELY SEEPING A THICK, SYRUPY FLUID AS I WATCHED.  I ALSO NOTED ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE DRAIN VALVE OPENING THAT THE METAL JACKET WALL WAS HEAVILY CORRODED.  I NOTED SEVERAL DENTS ALL OVER THE OUTSIDE

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON MAY 8, 2004, A MIDLAND-IMPACT, LLP DRIVER WAS DELIVERING 2 - 1000 GALLON ANHYDROUS AMMONIA (FERTILIZER) NURSE TANKS TO A FARMER CUSTOMER.  OUR DRIVER WAS EASTBOUND ON STATE ROAD 36 TURNING NORTH ON STATE ROAD 39, WHILE GOING THROUGH THE CORNER THE SECOND TANK OVERTURNED.  AS THE TANK OVERTURNED, THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE, LOCATED ON THE TOP OF THE TANK NEAR THE REAR, STRUCK THE CURB CAUSING A CRACK IN THE VALVE RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  THE PROTECTIVE GUARD AROUND THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE RESTRICTED ACCESS TO REPAIR THE CRACKED VALVE - WITH THE LIMITED ACCESS TO THE VALVE AND THE FACT THAT ANHYDROUS AMMONIA IS STORED UNDER PRESSURE, THE RELEASE OCCURRED RAPIDLY WITH LIMITED OPPORTUNITY TO REPAIR THE CRACKED VALVE.  ONCE THE RELEASE BEGAN THE DRIVER BEGAN IMMEDIATE EVACUATIONS OF THE BANK AND NEARBY RESIDENTS.  DANVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS ASSISTED WITH EVACUATIONS AND CONTROL OF THE SITE.  DANVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT USED A WATER FOG TO HELP CONTROL THE VAPOR CLOUD.  SOIL WAS APPLIED AS AN ABSORBENT FOR THE LIQUID AMMONIA THAT POOLED ON STATE ROAD 36 - APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS.  THE SOIL WAS RECLAIMED AND USED FOR ITS NORMAL USE AS A FERTILIZER.  NO HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS CREATED FROM THIS INCIDENT.  AS FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION FOR FUTURE EVENTS, WE ARE CONTACTING THE INDIANA STATE CHEMISTS OFFICE TO DISCUSS THE OPTION OF MANUFACTURING A SEALED "DOME" TO PLACE OVER A VALVE IN SITUATIONS SUCH AS THIS.  WITH THE PRODUCT BEING STORED UNDER PRESSURE, SPECIAL CONSIDERATION AND PRECAUTIONS MUST BE TAKEN.

column72: C I T X (PLM RAILCAR SERV CN)
column168: AT EMPLOYEE AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RICE YARD, WAYCROSS, GA REPORTED HE SMELLED AN AMMONIA ODOR WHILE WALKING BETWEEN TRACKS IN THE CLASS YD.  HE REPORTED THAT HE BECAME NAUSEATED AND VOMITED.  HE ALSO INDICATED HE FELT NUMB.  THE EMPLOYEE, MR. DERRICK TIPPENS, WAS TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR EXAMINATION.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED 5 ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CARS ON THE TRACK WHERE MR TIPPENS INDICATED HE BECAME ILL.  THE TRAINMASTER REPORTED HE DETECTED NO ODOR NOR SAW ANY SIGNS OF PRODUCT RELEASE.  ABOUT 1 HOUR LATER, THE TRAINMASTER WAS INSPECTING THE TRACK AGAIN WHEN THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CARS WERE MOVED.  HE REPORTED HE A SLIGHT AMMONIA ODOR AROUND TANK CAR, CITX 35528, LOAD ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  HE INSPECTED THE TOP OF THE CAR AND HEARD A SLIGHT HISSING SOUND COMING FROM INSIDE THE DOME AND HE REPORTED A MUCH STRONGER AMMONIA ODOR CLOSE TO THE DOME.  THE CITX 35528 WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER, CF INDUSTRIES, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE VAPOR RELEASE COMING THROUGH THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE O RINGS AND THE RETAINER IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AND THE VAPOR LEAKED STOPPED.  THE HOSPITAL CONDUCTED A BLOOD GAS TEST ON MR. TIPPENS AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF AMMONIA.  MR. TIPPENS WAS RELEASED AND RETURNED TO WORK THE NEXT DAY.

UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE ONE PAIL WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING A SPILL PAD AND PACKED INTO A BAG.  THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS SEALED AND RETURNED TO THE BROOK PARK, OH FACILITY.

SWIVEL JOINT AT HOSE REEL BROKE, SPILLING APPROX 6 1/2 GAL INTO STORM DRAIN.  GRANBY F.D., CT D.E.P., AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED CLEAN SPILL .  RELEASE STOPPED BY DRIVER WHO CLOSED THE BELLY VALVE.

column168: DRIVER WAS FILLING TANK.  BACK-PRESSURE CAUSED FILL PIPE TO 'SPURT' 1/2 CUP ONTO THE SIDING OF HOME.  NO EXPOSURE TO SOIL OR WATER.  CLEANED WITH RAGS & SIMPLE GREEN.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT WAS STOPPED FOR A ROADSIDE INSPECTION BY LOUISIANA STATE POLICE.  THE INSPECTOR NOTED A DRIP COMING FROM THE CARGO TANK BELLY VALVE.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED TO CATCH THE DRIPS AND CONTACTS WERE MADE TO THE UTI CONTROL BRANCH, LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY EMERGENCY RESPONSE, AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE RIGHT TO KNOW UNIT.  UTI CONTRACTED BEST PROBE ENVIRONMENTAL IN THE PERSON OF MARK TAYLOR TO RESPOND AND REMEDIATE THE AREA.  THE PRODUCT ON THE LEAKING TRAILER WAS TRANSLOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER.  UNDER THE DIRECT SUPERVISION OF THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (LDEQ) THE CONTAMINATED SURFACES WERE TREATED TWICE WITH A BAKING SODA SOLUTION TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID AND THEN RINSED OR WIPED DOWN.  THESE SURFACES WERE THEN TESTED AND APPROVED AS BEING SATISFACTORILY REMEDIATED BY THE LDEQ SUPERVISOR ON SITE.  ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED, MIXED WITH APPROXIMATELY HALF OF A DRUM OF CLEAN SOIL, AND SEALED INTO A DRUM FOR TRANSPORT TO THE OFFICE OF BEST PROBE ENVIRONMENTAL AT 24380 HIGHWAY 9, BIENVILLE, LA, PENDING TESTING AND DISPOSAL BY BEST PROBE ENVIRONMENTAL.  THE LEAKING TRAILER (NOW EMPTY AND NO LONGER LEAKING) WAS TAKEN TO A TANK WASH FACILITY TO BE WASHED OUT. THE CRIMPED BELLY VALVE GASKET WHICH HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY INSTALLED DURING PREVIOUS WASHOUT WAS REMOVED AND A NEW GASKET WAS PROPERLY INSTALLED.  THE TRAILER HAS BEEN RETURNED TO THE CONTROL BRANCH AND PARKED PENDING A THOROUGH INSPECTION PRIOR TO BEING PLACED BACK INTO SERVICE.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL SIX ALUMINUM CANS AT APPROXIMATELY ONE LITER CAPACITY EACH.  THE LID SEAL ON ONE OF THE CAN HAD FAILED ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  WHILE ATTEMPTING TO CONTAIN THE SPILL A FEDEX DANGEROUS GOODS AGENT, JOHN SULLIVAN GOT SOME OF THE SPILLED SUBSTANCE ON HIS HANDS CAUSING A BURNING, STINGING SENSATION.  HE WASHED HIS HANDS IMMEDIATELY AND CALLED THE SHIPPER FOR AN MSDS FOR THE PRODUCT.  THE DOCUMENT INDICATED THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS 93% SULPHURIC ACID. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT LUKE SHELTON/FAA/DFW/FTW AT 15:16(CST) ON 05/14/2004.

column168: TANK CAR GETX 3008 WAS INBOUND TO THE CLASSIFICATION YARD IN CUMBERLAND, MD.  DURING THE INBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A LIQUID (LATER DETERMINED TO BE ACETONE) WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE CAR.  THE AREA AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT TEAM WERE NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DETERMINED THAT DUE TO THE LIMITED AMOUNT OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED AND THE HIGH EVAPORATION RATE OF THE PRODUCT THAT THE SPILL DID NOT CONSTITUTE AN EMERGENCY AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT TO A TRACK CLOSEBY WHERE THE CAR COULD BE EXAMINED FURTHER AND TRANSLOADED.  AFTER CLOSER INSPECTION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE TANK SHELL NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR AND BEHIND AN ATTACHMENT RAIL THAT WAS WELDED ONTO THE CAR.  LIQUID WAS SEEN DRIPPING FROM THE OPEN, DOWN GRADIENT END OF THE ATTACHMENT RAIL.  DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE LEAK COULD NOT BE STOPPED, THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR WERE TRANSLOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS FOR DELIVERY TO THE FINAL CUSTOMER(S).  THE CAR WAS THEN CLEANED AND PURGED OF ANY REMAINING ACETONE PRIOR TO MOVEMENT TO A TANK  CAR REPAIR FACILITY.  A MOVEMENT EXEMPTION (FRA-04051360) WAS OBTAINED FOR MOVEMENT OF THE CAR FROM CUMBERLAND, MD TO DUBOIS, PA.
UNDECLARED  LEAKING PACKAGE DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY.
UNDECLARED  LEAKING PACKAGE DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED FIFTY POUND PAPER BAG WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY, THREE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING, NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WAS PLACED TO SECURE THE BAG.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, SUITS, MASKS AND A BROOM AND SHOVEL.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE DAMAGED BAG WAS PLACED INTO ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURE WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

SPILL OCCURRED ON 17 MAY 2004, APPROXIMATELY 05:30 AM DURING THE OFF LOADING OF THE AIRCRAFT A STRANGE ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE OFF LOADING CONTINUED THE PALLET WAS TOWED TO THE WAREHOUSE.  THEY THEN DISCOVERED THE RUPTURE TO THE DRUM.  THE WAREHOUSE WAS EVACUATED.  THE PORT AUTHORITY HAZMAT TEAM WAS CALLED THEY CAME OVER WITH THE MEDICAL TEAM, WHO EXAMINED 15 OF THE WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL WHO CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE SPILL, THEY WERE ALL RELEASED WITH NO INJURIES OR COMPLICATIONS.  PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHED REPORTS FOR MORE INFORMATION.  THE DANGEROUS GOODS WERE TRANSPORTED ON POLAR AIR CARGO'S, ("POLAR") FLIGHT NUMBER PO411, 17 MAY 2004 FROM PRESTWICK, SCOTLAND, ENGLAND TO JOHN F. KENNEDY INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT, JAMAICA, NY.  A SPILL OF UN2572, PHENYLHYDRAZINE, CLASS 6.1 FROM A METAL DRUM OCCURRED DURING THE UNLOADING OF THE AIRCRAFT.  THE SPILL OCCURRED ON 17 MAY 2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 05:35 AM.  DURING THE OFF-LOAD OF THE AIRCRAFT, ALLIANCE (POLAR'S GROUND HANDLER) RAMP CREW MEMBER MR. ZIGGY DUCHNOWSKI, NOTICED A STRANGE ODOR COMING FROM PALLET PMC0351PO.  HE INFORMED HIS SUPERVISOR, MR. DAVID GRAJKO.  THE CREW CONTINUED THE OFF-LOADING AND REMOVED THE PALLET IN QUESTION FROM THE PLANE AND PLACED IT ON A DOLLIE DRIVER FOR THE CREW, MR. JOHN LESTER, NOTICED THE ODOR AS WELL BUT COULD NOT SEE ANY VISIBLE LEAKS ON THE PALLET.  THE DOLLIE WITH THE PALLET WAS PLACED OUTSIDE THE POLAR AIR CARGO'S WAREHOUSE BUILDING 87 AT JFK INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT AT RAMP AREA 4.  THE PALLET WAS THEN TAKEN INTO THE WAREHOUSE BY THE ALLIANCE WAREHOUSE BREAKDOWN STAFF AND THE PALLET BREAKDOWN COMMENCED.  IT WAS THEN DISCOVERED THERE WAS A RUPTURE ON THE DRUM.  THE ALLIANCE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED CAMILLE DORAN, POLAR AIR CARGO STATION REPRESENTATIVE.  HE GAVE HER THE PALLET TAG AND THE LABEL FROM THE STEEL DRUM.  MS. DORAN CONSULTED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE AND FOLLOWED THE SPILL, LEAK AND FIRST AID PROCEDURES FOR GUIDE #153.  SHE EVACUATED THE AREA AND IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE PORT AUTHORITY POLICE, WHO IN TURN CONTACTED THE PA HAZMAT TEAM.  PORT AUTHORITY POLICE OFFICER COFIELD, ALONG WITH PORT AUTHORITY SERGEANT FARROW AND HIS HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED AT THE WAREHOUSE AT 06:00 AM, THE WAREHOUSE AND RAMP AREA WERE EVACUATED.  THE RAMP AND WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL, 15 IN TOTAL, WHO CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE PALLET AND THE FUMES WERE EXAMINED AND RELEASED WITH NO INJURIES BY THE MEDICAL PERSONNEL AT THE SITE.  THE HAZMAT SPILL TEAM WAS PREPARED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL, BUT NONE OF THE LIQUID REMAINED AS IT HAD ALL EVAPORATED.  APPROXIMATELY 3 LITERS OF THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED AS PER THE REPORTS RECEIVED.  IT APPEARS THE DAMAGE WAS CAUSED BY DURING THE OFF-LOADING OF THE PALLET FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  WE BELIEVE THE DRUM MIGHT HAVE BEEN STRUCK WITH ANOTHER PALLET OR LOCKING SYSTEM.

column168: SEVERAL PALLETS LOADED WITH 5 GALLON BUCKETS WERE STAGED ON THE DOCK WAITING TO BE LOADED.  KERRY OSBORNE WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MOVING THE FREIGHT FROM THE DOCK TO AN OUTBOUND TRAILER.  THE PALLETS WERE STAGED ON THE DOCK VERY TIGHT TOGETHER WITHOUT ANY SPACE IN BETWEEN THEM.  KERRY NOTICE A PECULIAR ODOR IN THE AREA AS HE WAS WORKING THE FREIGHT BUT DID NOT SEE ANY EVIDENCE OF A LEAK.  AS HE RETURNED TO THE AREA AFTER LOADING A PALLET ONTO A TRAILER, HE OBSERVED A PUDDLE FORMING UNDERNEATH THE NEXT PALLET TO BE MOVED.  WHEN HE LIFTED UP THAT PALLET, HE SAW THAT A BUCKET LOADED ON THE SECOND ROW, MIDDLE COLUMN OF THE NEXT PALLET HAD A SMALL, ROUND PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE SIDE, AND WAS LEAKING A STEADY STREAM OF FLUID. MY OPINION IS THAT KERRY PUNCTURED ONE OF THE THIN SIDEWALLS OF THE BUCKETS BY PUSHING THE PALLETS TOGETHER.  THE SIDE WALLS ON THE PALES ARE VERY THIN AND CAN BE EASILY CAVED IN WITH ONLY THUMB PRESSURE.  WHERE THE RIGID STEEL HANDLES OF THE BUCKETS ARE MOUNTED TO THE SIDE WALLS THEY MAKE A 90 DEGREE BEND.  I THINK THAT ONE OF THESE HANDLES WAS SHOVED AGAINST ONE OF THE BUCKETS AND PUNCTURED IT.

column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: OUR DRIVER WENT TO DROP GASOHOL AT KUM AND GO, FORT DODGE, IOWA.  THERE WAS SOME CONFUSION ABOUT WHICH TANK IS NL (NO LEAD) AND WHICH TANK IS N+ (GASOHOL).  THE TANK WITH THE YELLOW LID (SHOULD MEAN N+) HAS A FILL TUBE TAG THAT READS UNLEADED REGULAR, 10,000 GALLONS.  THE TANK WITH THE WHITE LID (SHOULD BE NL) HAS A FILL TUBE TAG THAT READ GASOHOL, 6,000.  OUR DRIVER CONTACTED THE STORE ASSOCIATE WHO CALLED MANAGER TO FIND OUT WHICH TANK WAS WHAT.  HE WAS TOLD THAT THE 10,000 GALLON TANK WAS THE GASOHOL TANK.  OUR DRIVER LOOKED INSIDE AND FOUND THE TANK THAT WAS DESIGNATED AS THE 10,000 GALLON TANK.  HE STAKED THE TANK AND CAME UP WITH 31 1/2 INCHES, WHICH MEANS IT WOULD FIT IN THE 10,000 GALLON TANK.  HE WAS UNLOADING THE GASOHAUL AND THE TANK STARTED TO OVER FILL SPILLING 50-60 GALLONS OF FUEL. WE CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AT 515-573-2871.  CAPTAIN TERRY MIKITO WAS THE PERSON IN CHARGE AT THE SCENE.  THEY PUT DOWN 20 POUNDS OF KITTY LITTER AND CALLED THE CITY CREW TO PUT DOWN SAND.  CAPTAIN MIKITO TOLD OUR NIGHT DISPATCH, SCOTT CRUM, EVERYTHING WAS DONE TO HIS SATISFACTION.  THE NEXT DAY WE HIRED HOVEY CONSTRUCTION, FORT DODGE, IOWA, TO GO THE SCENE AND CLEAN UP THE KITTY LITTER AND SAND.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PUT IN THE REGIONAL LANDFILL IN FORT DODGE, IOWA.  CORRECTION ACTION: THE LIDS OF THE TANKS ARE NOW PAINTED THE CORRECT COLOR FOR THE TAG THAT IS PUT ON THE FILL TUBE AND THE PLATES SHOWING THE SIZE OF THE TANK HAVE BEEN SWITCHED TO THE CORRECT TANKS.

column168: TOD JACKSON, YARD MASTER, ROSEBLUFF YARD, LAKE CHARLES, LOUISIANA, ADVISED THREE YARD EMPLOYEES WERE COMPLAINING OF RAW THROATS AND WATERY EYES.  MR. JACKSON FURTHER ADVISED THAT THE EMPLOYEES HAVE BEEN COMPLAINING OF THESE SYMPTOMS FOR THE PAST TWO DAYS.  THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED.  LOUISIANA STATE NOTIFICATIONS WAS ALSO MADE.  MR. ROBINSON ADVISED THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT THE ROSEBLUFF YARD, IN LAKE CHARLES LOUISIANA.  HE ADVISED THAT DALE BREAUX, MANAGER OF OPERATING PRACTICES, TRANSPORTED THREE UNION PACIFIC CREW MEMBERS TO THE SAINT PATS HOSPITAL.  MR. ROBINSON ADVISED THAT RAILCARS GATX 51956 AND GATX 51976 ARE IN THE YARD AND CONTAIN ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  THE RAIL CARS ARE LOCATED ON KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN TRACK #3 AT THE WEST END OF THE YARD AND HAD BEEN INTERCHANGED TO THE KCS ON 05/03/04.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.  AT 11:59 PM, MANAGER ROBINSON ADVISED HE HAD MADE CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, AND HULCHER SERVICES WOULD BE ENROUTE TO INSPECT THE RAILCARS.  THE EXPOSED EMPLOYEES HAD BEEN EXAMINED AND RELEASED FROM THE MEDICAL FACILITY, AND HAD RETURNED TO THE YARD FOR PAPERWORK.  ON THURSDAY, 5/6/04, AT 5:30 AM, ROBINSON REPORTED BOTH TANKCARS HAD BEEN SECURED.  THE O-RINGS ON THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVES ON BOTH TANKCARS WERE SAFETY REPLACED.  BOTH CARS WERE RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.  AT 4:11PM, CHRIS, YARDMASTER, ADVISED THAT EMPLOYEES WERE STILL COMPLAINING OF AN ODOR IN THE YARD.  TIMOTHY O'BRIEN, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND CHET CULLEY, HAZMAT, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN BOTH BE NOTIFIED.  DALE BREAUX, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, ADVISED BOTH TANK CARS WERE VENTING.  MANAGER LERCH ADVISED HULCHER SERVICES WAS RESPONDING AND THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAD BEEN NOTIFIED.  BRANDON SIMON WITH THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY ALSO RESPONDED.  ON 5/07/04, AT 01:18 AM, MANAGER LERCH REPORTED THAT WHEN HE ARRIVED, HE WAS MET BY LOUISIANA STATE POLICE.  THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE TANKCAR CONTRACTOR IN AN EFFECT TO STOP THE RELEASE FROM THE CARS.  MR. LERCH STATED THAT UPON INSPECTION, VAPOR PRODUCT WAS FOUND LEAKING FROM THE SEAL ON THE PRESSURE PLATE.  MR. LERCH ADVISED THAT HULCHER SERVICES WOULD STAY WITH THE AFFECTED CARS AND KCS HAS ACCEPTED SAID CARS.

column168: AT 1230HRS CTS MGR LERCH RESPONDED TO LEAKING TANK CAR TEIX 30177, LOCATED IN TRACK 205, SETTEGAST YARD; HOUSTON, TX.  UPON ARRIVAL MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP AT A RATE OF LESS THAN ONE GALLON PER HOUR. column168: ICTF SECURITY REPORTED CONTAINER POCU 032977, WAS LEAKING TOW DROPS A SECOND AND ON SPOT AT THE CUSTOMS DOCK IN THE ICTF YARD, LONG BEACH, CA. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND FOUND THE LADING TO CONSIST OF TWELVE EACH, 275 GALLON TOTES, DOUBLE STACKED, WITH NO BI-LEVEL SEPARATION.  3X8 LUMBER HAD BEEN USED TO SECURE THE VOID SPACE TO THE REAR DOOR THAT WAS NOT TO BOE 6C STANDARD.  THERE WERE RESIDUE STAINS ON THE FLOORING TO THE REAR OF THE TOTES, HOWEVER, THERE WERE NO ACTIVE LEAKS OBSERVED.  AN AREA DIRECTLY UNDER THE NOSE OF THE CONTAINER HAD A STAIN THAT APPEARED TO BE NO LARGER THAN FIVE TO SIX OUNCES OF DRIED LIQUID N THE GROUND.  FIELD TESTING WAS INCONCLUSIVE.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH P&O TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE TOTES.  ONE TOTE WAS FOUND WITH A LOOSE TOP CLOSURE, WHICH RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT BEING RELEASED.  THE WIRE SEAL WAS CUT AND THE TOP CLOSURE SECURED.  THE TOTE WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE.  THE FLOORING OF THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WAS ALSO CLEANED, AND THE CONTAINER RELEASED BACK TO P&O.  AS THE TOTES WERE DOUBLE STACKED IN THE ORIGINAL 20 FOOT CONTAINER, P&O WAS REQUESTED TO PROVIDE A 40 CONTAINER SO THE TOTES COULD BE LOADED FOR THE RAIL MOVE TO PENNSYLVANIA.  THE TRANSFER CONTAINER, PONU 160996, WAS DELIVERED THE FOLLOWING DAY.  THE TOTES WERE LOADED, AND PROPERLY SECURED FOR RAIL MOVEMENT.  ONCE THE BILLING IS TRANSFERRED TO THE NEW CONTAINER, IT WILL BE RELEASED FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

SCHLUMBERGER-LONGVIEW IS SUBMITTING A WRITTEN NOTIFICATION DESCRIBING A REPORTABLE DIESEL SPILL THAT OCCURRED AROUND 01:00 A.M. ON MAY 6, 2004 ON OR AROUND OUR PROPERTY LOCATED AT 801 STANDARD ST., LONGVIEW, TEX 75604. AT 07:00 AM ON MAY 6, 2004, SCHLUMBERGER SHOP PERSONNEL NOTICED OFF-ROAD DIESEL ENTERING A CEMENT DITCH ON OUR PROPERTY.  WE IMMEDIATELY DIKED UP THIS DITCH AND BEGAN CLEAN UP.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, WE FOUND THAT SOME OF THE DIESEL AND BEGAN CLEAN UP.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, WE FOUND THAT SOME OF THE DIESEL HAD LEFT OUR PROPERTY AND ENTERED A CREEK (UN-NAMED) ACROSS FROM OUR PROPERTY.  WE PLACED BOOMS AND DIAPERS TO STOP THE DIESEL FROM TRAVELING ANY FURTHER.  IN ADDITION, WE NOTIFIED GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO HELP WITH THE CLEAN UP.  ALL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE, INCLUDING ONE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER -- REPORT #721020 CAUSE OF SPILL:  BULK PLANT OPERATOR WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LOADING J916 INTO A SLURRY MIXER SENT TO LONGVIEW FROM A SISTER DISTRICT.  OPERATOR HAD LOADED 1045 GALLONS OF DIESEL INTO EACH TANK AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF SETTING UP TO BLOW IN THE DRY GEL FROM THE WEIGH BATCHER WHEN HE REALIZED THAT THIS PARTICULAR UNIT WAS NOT SET UP TO BLOW DRY GEL INTO IT.  THE OPERATOR HAD TO REMOVE A 4-INCH BLANKING CAP ON BOTH TANKS.  ON THE FRONT TANK, HE PLACED A CAP WITH A 2-INCH BALL VALVE IN IT TO BE ABLE TO CIRCULATE THE TANK.  OPERATOR THEN CONTINUED THE PROCESS.  WITH APPROX. 30# OF GEL LEFT TO LOAD INTO TANK 1, THE LINE PLUGGED OFF.  OPERATOR SWITCHED TANKS SO THAT HE COULD UNPLUG LINE, FAILING TO REALIZE THAT HE HAD REMOVED THE BLANKING CAP ON THE SECOND TANK AND HAD NOT PUT THE CAP WITH THE BALL VALVE IN ITS PLACE.  IN DOING SO DIESEL WAS PUMPED ONTO THE GROUND AND SUBSEQUENTLY RAN DOWN HILL INTO DRAINAGE DITCH, AND ULTIMATELY INTO SMALL CREEK ADJACENT TO FACILITY.  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO EFFECT CLEANUP, AND AN ESTIMATED 200 GALLONS OF DIESEL WAS RECOVERED AND CLEANUP MADE TO ALL PARTY'S SATISFACTION.  NATIONAL RESPONSE REPORT #721020 FOR THIS INCIDENT.  ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENT: ALL UNITS WILL BE FITTED WITH PROPER EQUIPMENT FOR LOADING.  ALL PERSONNEL ATTEND SAFETY AND OPERATIONS MEETING TO DISCUSS THIS INCIDENT AND WAYS TO PREVENT IT FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.  OPERATOR RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS INCIDENT WAS TERMINATED.
